<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="88" pageId="6" pageNumber="87" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1322,2034]" lastBlockId="7.[151,1436,151,321]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="88" pageId="6" pageNumber="87">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1971,1997]" pageId="6" pageNumber="87">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schilder" baseAuthorityYear="1933" box="[323,599,1971,1997]" class="Gastropoda" family="Triviidae" genus="Archierato" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="6" pageNumber="87" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="galapagensis">
<emphasis box="[323,599,1971,1997]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="87">Archierato galapagensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is restricted to the 
<collectingRegion box="[815,933,1971,1997]" country="Ecuador" name="Galapagos" pageId="6" pageNumber="87">Galapagos</collectingRegion>
Archipelago. Unfortunately, 
<bibRefCitation author="Schilder, F. A." pageId="6" pageNumber="87" pagination="244 - 283" refId="ref15697" refString="Schilder, F. A. (1933) Monograph of the Subfamily Eratoinae. Proceedings of the Malacological Society London, 20 (5), 244 - 283. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / oxfordjournals. mollus. a 064197" type="journal article" year="1933">Schilder (1933: 249</bibRefCitation>
, 254, 264) based his description on a beached and damaged 
<typeStatus box="[860,962,2007,2033]" pageId="6" pageNumber="87">holotype</typeStatus>
. Therefore, its coloration is not representative. However, the shell morphology is distinctive from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fehse &amp; Simone" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Menke" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[779,934,151,177]" class="Gastropoda" family="Triviidae" genus="Archierato" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="7" pageNumber="88" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="columbella">
<emphasis box="[779,934,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">A. columbella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fehse &amp; Simone" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Carpenter" baseAuthorityYear="1856" box="[989,1166,151,177]" class="Gastropoda" family="Triviidae" genus="Archierato" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="7" pageNumber="88" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="panamaensis">
<emphasis box="[989,1166,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">A. panamaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The ovate shell outline is in great contrast to the pyriform shells of the latter two species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,321]" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">
Rather smooth specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="DFB" baseAuthorityName="Gray in Sowerby I" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[537,830,223,249]" class="Gastropoda" family="Triviidae" genus="Hespererato" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="7" pageNumber="88" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="scabriuscula">
<emphasis box="[537,830,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">Hespererato scabriuscula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are usually offered by shell dealers and others (e.g. Femorale website) as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schilder" baseAuthorityYear="1933" box="[402,586,259,285]" class="Gastropoda" family="Triviidae" genus="Archierato" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="7" pageNumber="88" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="galapagensis">
<emphasis box="[402,586,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">H. galapagensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schilder" baseAuthorityYear="1933" box="[719,900,259,285]" class="Gastropoda" family="Triviidae" genus="Archierato" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="7" pageNumber="88" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="galapagensis">
<emphasis box="[719,900,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">A. galapagensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a much smaller species with finer dentition, narrow aperture and completely smooth shell.
</paragraph>
